data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed sync-over-async via an opt-in flag (e.g., `CosmosOptionsExtension` / `EnableSyncExecution`). **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call on the Cosmos provider now throws `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally.

### Affected calls in your code

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(…)` | `.FirstAsync(…)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key things to address

1. **Remove the opt-in config** — the flag no longer exists and will cause a build error.
2. **Propagate `async/await` up the call stack** — callers of these methods must also become async (controllers, services, etc.).
3. **Don't wrap with `.Result` / `.Wait()`** — that recreates the sync-over-async anti-pattern and risks deadlocks.
